## Practical and Ethical Challenges

### Inconsistent Application

Capital punishment is often applied inconsistently, with only a small minority of murderers actually executed in countries like the U.S. This randomness violates the principle of equal justice and undermines retributive claims ([BBC Ethics](https://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/capitalpunishment/against_1.shtml)).

### Cost and Resource Allocation

Contrary to some beliefs, the death penalty is often more expensive than life imprisonment due to lengthy and complex legal processes, including appeals and special incarceration requirements ([LawAspect](https://lawaspect.com/virtue-ethics-capital-punishment/)).

### Psychological and Moral Impact

Executing a human being, even humanely, involves moral and psychological burdens on those involved in the process, including executioners, legal professionals, and society at large ([HubPages](https://discover.hubpages.com/education/Capital-Punishment-and-Ethical-Theories)).

